3170 7/71

Oysters President Special.
Back in the days of fifteen course meals, Diamond Jim Brady
achieved legendary fame as this nation's champion bonvivant
and thought nothing of consuming eight to twelve dozen
giant oysters as a mere prelude to meals.
Creole Jambalaya.
The original recipe was introduced to the South during the
1700's by the Spanish, and consisted mainly of ham. The
Creole cooks, with their usual flair, added Gulf Shrimp and
other spices and herbs.
Sourdough Rolls.
Possibly the oldest of bread recipes dating as far back as 4000
B.C. It is made with a sourdough "starter,
" a self perpetuat-
ing yeast mixture made with a combination of flour, sugar
and water. This bread became identified in America through
its use by the Alaskan Sourdoughs, prospectors who carried
sourdough starters strapped to their packs so that they could
make bread anytime they wanted without having to walk to
the nearest town, usually miles away.
Waldorf Salad.
The original recipe was created by one of the most famous
of Maîtres d'Hôtel, Oscar of the Waldorf.
Salt Water Taffy.
This candy, almost a tradition is sold along the boardwalk
at Atlantic City. Rumor has it that it is made with sea water.
Cover.
One of a series of photographs depicting Early 19th Century
cooking utensils from New England, in wood, tin, ceramic,
cast and handwrought iron.
